'''Princess Hashihito no Anahobe''' (穴穂部間人皇女, ''Anahobe no Hashihito no Himemiko,'' 560 – 7 February 622<ref>朝日日本歴史人物事典：（株）朝日新聞出版. “穴穂部間人皇女”. コトバンク. 2021st year 9月6日閲覧</ref>), also known as '''Empress Taiza''' (間人皇后), was a member of the {{ill|Imperial House of Japan|en|Imperial House of Japan|WD=Q909452|lt=Japanese imperial family|1=Imperial House of Japan}} in the {{ill|Asuka period|en|Asuka period|WD=Q210688|lt=Asuka period|1=Asuka period}}. She was the {{ill|Empress of Japan|en|Empress of Japan|WD=Q595038|lt=empress consort|1=Empress of Japan}} through her marriage to {{ill|Emperor Yōmei|en|Emperor Yōmei|WD=Q349281|lt=Emperor Yōmei|1=Emperor Yōmei}}.

It is said that {{ill|Prince Shōtoku|en|Prince Shōtoku|WD=Q263972|lt=Prince Shōtoku|1=Prince Shōtoku}}, Princess Anahobe's eldest son, built the {{ill|Chūgū-ji|en|Chūgū-ji|WD=Q1091232|lt=Chūgū-ji|1=Chūgū-ji}} temple for his mother. The temple is located in {{ill|Ikaruga|en|Ikaruga|WD=Q1658068|lt=Ikaruga|1=Ikaruga}}, {{ill|Yamato Province|en|Yamato Province|WD=Q907495|lt=Yamato Province|1=Yamato Province}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|en|Nara Prefecture|WD=Q131287|lt=Nara Prefecture|1=Nara Prefecture}}, {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|WD=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}.

[[File:Chūgū-ji temple , 中宮寺 - panoramio (4).jpg|thumb|Chūgū-ji temple]]

== Genealogy ==
Princess Hashihito no Anahobe was born into the ruling clan of Japan. She was the daughter of {{ill|Emperor Kinmei|en|Emperor Kinmei|WD=Q329792|lt=Emperor Kinmei|1=Emperor Kinmei}} and his consort, Soga no Oane. The princess has five full brothers: two elder brother and three younger brothers. One of her younger brother will later become {{ill|Emperor Sushun|en|Emperor Sushun|WD=Q349238|lt=Emperor Sushun|1=Emperor Sushun}}.

In 574, Princess Hashihito no Anahobe married her eldest half-brother, [[:en:Yōmei|Imperial Prince Ōe]], born by another consort of the emperor. Their mothers were full sisters, making them cousins. The marriage produce four sons among which none of them ascended the throne. On 3 October 585, prince Ōe became emperor and Princess Hashihito no Anahobe was named Empress Consort ({{ill|Kōkyū|en|Kōkyū|WD=Q13403578|lt=Chūgū|1=Kōkyū}}) in January of the same year. Sadly, her husband died three years later after his ascension.

The widowed Empress married her stepson, Prince Tame, born by her husband's concubine, who also was her full sister.the couple had only one daughter.

* First Husband: {{ill|Emperor Yōmei|en|Emperor Yōmei|WD=Q349281|lt=Emperor Yōmei|1=Emperor Yōmei}} (用明天皇,  517 – 21 May 587), her half-brother and cousin
** Son: {{ill|Prince Shōtoku|en|Prince Shōtoku|WD=Q263972|lt=Prince Shōtoku|1=Prince Shōtoku}} (聖徳太子, Shōtoku Taishi, 7 February  574 – 8 April  622)
** Son: Prince Kume (来目皇子, d.603)
** Son: Prince Eguri (殖栗皇子)
** Son: Prince Mamuta (茨田皇子, 579-643)
* Second Husband: Prince Tame (田目皇子), her nephew and stepson
** Daughter: Princess Satōmi (佐富女王), Wife of Prince Hatsuse no Okimi (son of {{ill|Prince Shōtoku|en|Prince Shōtoku|WD=Q263972|lt=Prince Shōtoku|1=Prince Shōtoku}})
There is a famous anecdote in "[[Nihon Shoki|Nihonshoki]]" (Chronicles of Japan) that when Princess Hashihito no Anahobe was the empress of the Emperor Yōmei, she gave birth to the Prince Umayado ({{ill|Prince Shōtoku|en|Prince Shōtoku|WD=Q263972|lt=Prince Shotoku|1=Prince Shōtoku}}) at Umaya no toguchi (a door of a {{ill|stable|en|stable|WD=Q214252|lt=stable|1=Stable}}).

